Part 1: Data

The GSS gathers data on contemporary American society in order to monitor and explain trends and constants in attitudes, behaviors, and attributes. It was first conducted in 1972 and was carried out annually until 1994, except in 1979, 1981, and 1992. Since 1994, the GSS has been conducted in even numbered years. The data for this project include responses to a total of 114 variables from the years 1972 to 2012.

The target population of the GSS is adults (18+) living in households in the United States. Before 2004, the survey was restricted to those who can only respond in English. From 2006 to present it has included those able to do the survey in English or Spanish. Additionally, those unable to do the survey in either English or Spanish are out-of-scope. Residents of institutions and group quarters are out-of-scope. Those with mental and/or physical conditions that prevent them from doing the survey, but who live in households are part of the target population and in-scope. Therefore while in general we can consider GSS uses a simple random sampling method, certain populations are excluded from the surveys and therefore any generalizations need to be made with caution.

The vast majority of GSS data is obtained in face-to-face interviews. Computer-assisted personal interviewing (CAPI) began in the 2002 GSS. Under some conditions when it has proved difficult to arrange an in-person interview with a sampled respondent, GSS interviews may be conducted by telephone. The use of multiple interview schemes allows the data to be more presentative than if relying on a single scheme.

The target sample size for the annual surveys from 1972 to 1993 was 1500. Since 1994 the GSS has been administered to two samples in even-numbered years, each with a target sample size of 1500, rather than to a single 1500-person sample each year. In 2006, a third sample was added and the sample size was 4510. Furthermore, as noted in the GSS appendix, the samples for the 1972 through to 1974 surveys follows a modified probability design, introducing the quota element at the block level, whereas for later surveys, full probability sample design has been adopted.

The GSS is an observation study. While its findings can be generalized to the wider American soiety with caution noted above, these can not be considered evidence for any causal relationship among the variables.

Part 2: Research question

The analysis in this report seeks to investigate if peoples attitudes towards suicide as a result of incurable disease have changed over the years from 1972 to 2012, as well as whether such attitudes differ among people having different religious practice or political views. This research question has been selected because the issue of abortion has always been subject to debate and Im interested in finding out if and how the situation changed over the years, and whether such attitudes are influenced by peoples religion and political views.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

To address the research question, 3 variables are selected for analysis. These are: 1. attend (how often the participant attends religious services) 2. polviews (how liberal or conservative the participant considers themselves) 3. suicide1 (attitude towards suicide if the person has incurable disease)

Part 4: Inference

Part 3 presents the summary data needed to address the research question: have peoples attitudes towards suicide as a result of incurable disease changed over the years from 1972 to 2012? Are such attitudes influenced by peoples religious practice and political views? While the initial analysis seems to indicate yes to both inquiries, we need to find out if the differences noticed could be due to chance, or indeed significant. To achieve this, first a hypothesis test will be conducted to see if the there is a significant difference in peoples attitude towards suicide between 1977 and 2012. Then a chi-square test for testing independence will be conducted to examine if the attitude to suicide is dependent on political views, or religious practice.

To find out if peoples attitude changed from 1977 to 2012 to suicide as a result of incurable disease, two points of estimates are chosen, the yes proportion in 1977, 37.5% (p1), and that in 2012, 54.8% (p2). The number of participants who responded to this question in is 1208 (n1) in 1977, and 885 (n2)in 2012. As here we are working with two categorical variables and each only has two levels, both hypothesis test and confidence interval method are used to check if there is any significant difference between the two proportions.

The null hypothesis is that peoples attitude to suicide hasnt changed: p1=p2. The alternative hypothesis is peoples attitude is different: p1!=p2.

Now lets check if the conditions are met for hypothesis testing and confidence interval of the difference between the two proportions. Judging from the survey description, its reasonable to believe that participants to the surveys were selected using simple random sampling method and hence they are independent both within and between the groups.Its also reasonable to assume that either of the sample size is less than 10% of the population size.

Using the pooled proportion, this success-failure condition is satisfied for hypothesis test. Use p1 and p2, the success-failure condition is also satisfied for calculating confidence interval of the difference. The code below shows the calculation process. Significance level for the hypothesis test is 0.05, and the confidence interval is 95%.

table(gss_suicide$year, gss_suicide$suicide1)
##       
##        Yes  No
##   1977 453 755
##   1978 425 748
##   1982 589 857
##   1983 306 342
##   1985 516 695
##   1986 600 567
##   1988 370 370
##   1989 344 404
##   1990 407 302
##   1991 459 357
##   1993 469 353
##   1994 919 576
##   1996 905 554
##   1998 798 551
##   2000 694 587
##   2002 400 306
##   2004 404 291
##   2006 802 602
##   2008 545 418
##   2010 572 453
##   2012 485 400
#decide on the points of estimate: the yes proportion of responses.
p1<-0.375
p2<-0.548
n1<-1208
n2<-885
#null hypothesis is p1-p2=0, alternative hypothesis is p1-p2!=0
#checking success-failure conditions 
p_pooled<-(453+485)/(1208+885)
p_pooled
## [1] 0.4481605
#caculate the standard error se-pooled used for p1-p2 in hypothesis testing
se1<-sqrt(p_pooled*(1-p_pooled)/n1+p_pooled*(1-p_pooled)/n2)
se1
## [1] 0.02200405
#calculate the standard error used for p1-p2 in calculating confidence intervals
se2<-sqrt(0.375*(1-0.375)/1208+0.548*(1-0.548)/885)
se2
## [1] 0.02176928
#calculating zscore
pdiff<-p1-p2
pdiff
## [1] -0.173
zscore<-pdiff/se1
zscore
## [1] -7.862188
#Finding the pvalue of corresponding to the zscore
pvalue<-pnorm(zscore, lower.tail=TRUE)*2
pvalue
## [1] 3.774818e-15
#Calculating the 95% confidence interval for the difference between p1 and p2
ci_95<-c("upper"=(p1-p2)+1.96*se2, "lower"=(p1-p2)-1.96*se2)
ci_95
##      upper      lower 
## -0.1303322 -0.2156678
#alternatively, use the prop.test function
x<-c(453, 485)
n<-c(1208, 885)
prop.test(x, n, p=NULL, alternative=c("two.sided"), conf.level = 0.95, correct = FALSE)
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity
##  correction
## 
## data:  x out of n
## X-squared = 61.83, df = 1, p-value = 3.744e-15
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2156895 -0.1303557
## sample estimates:
##    prop 1    prop 2 
## 0.3750000 0.5480226

As shown above, both methods generate the same result. p-value for hypothesis testing of the difference between the two proportions is much smaller than 0.05 and therefore we reject the null hypothesis: there is strong evidence indicating that peoples attitude towards abortion has indeed changed from 1977 to 2012. The 95% confidence interval for the difference between the two proportions (p1-p2) is -0.216 and -0.130, meaning we are 95% confident that the proportion of people who agree with suicide because of incurable disease in 1977 is 13% to 21.6% lower than those in 2012. 0 is not within this range. Therefore the result aligns with the hypothesis testing.

Having tested that there has been a significant change from 1977 to 2012 in peoples attitude to suicide because of incurable disease, now lets check if this attitude is dependent on how often people attend to church services. Chi-square test for independence is selected because we are working with two categorical variables and one of them, attend, has more than 2 levels.

To check the conditions for using chi-square test, its reasonable to believe that a simple random sampling method is used in collecting survey data, despite the existence of certain bias in sampling as noted in part 1. Therefor we can assume that the independence condition is met. We can also assume the sample size is less than 10% of the population. Chi-square test requires each scenario has at least 5 cases. Therefore we need to remove never from the analysis since its 0 for both yes and no for this option.

Following this we can see the numbers of yes and no responses presented in the table below for each group of respondents. The null hypothesis is peoples response to suicide because of incurable disease is independent on how often they go to church. The alternative hypothesis is that their responses are dependent on how often they go to church. Below shows the process of conducting the chi-square testing for independence.

#drop the Never level that has 0 response
gss_suicide1<-gss_suicide%>%
  filter(attend != "Never")%>%droplevels()
#table to show the count of yes and no responses for each category
table(gss_suicide1$attend, gss_suicide1$suicide1)
##                   
##                     Yes   No
##   Lt Once A Year   1443  605
##   Once A Year      2514 1089
##   Sevrl Times A Yr 2060 1156
##   Once A Month     1160  798
##   2-3X A Month     1262 1150
##   Nrly Every Week   615  805
##   Every Week       1994 3291
##   More Thn Once Wk  414 1594
chisq<-chisq.test(table(gss_suicide1$attend, gss_suicide1$suicide1))
chisq
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(gss_suicide1$attend, gss_suicide1$suicide1)
## X-squared = 2231, df = 7, p-value < 2.2e-16

Using the significance level 0.05, p-value is incredibly smaller, therefore we reject the null hypothesis that the two variables are independent. There is strong evidence suggesting peoples attitude to suicide as a result of incurable disease is related to how often they go to church.

Just out of curiosity, I would like to see the proportion of respondents who go to church at difference frequency over the years survey was conducted from 1977 to 2012 and whether there is noticble difference in such proportion. This is because given the test above showing that peoples attitude to suicide are related to their religious practice, the difference in proportion of respondents would have an effect on the overall responses when we consider the difference across years. Here Im not going to test if there is significant difference in such proportions but just to take a quick look at the results below and keep that in mind. Last, lets check if this attitude is dependent on peoples political views using chi-square test for independence. Chi-square test is again chosen because we are looking at the relationship between two categorical variables and the variable polviews had more than two levels.

Similar to the previous chi-square test, we can assume that the independence condition is met and the sample size is less than 10% of the population. Chi-square test requires each scenario has at least 5 cases and this condition is also met.

In the table below we can see the numbers of yes and no responses for each group of respondents. The null hypothesis is peoples response to suicide because of incurable disease is independent on their political views. The alternative hypothesis is that their responses are dependent on their political views. Below shows the process of conducting the chi-square testing for independence.

table(gss_suicide$polviews, gss_suicide$suicide1)
##                         
##                           Yes   No
##   Extremely Liberal       331  194
##   Liberal                1446  861
##   Slightly Liberal       1732 1117
##   Moderate               4336 3983
##   Slightly Conservative  1889 1761
##   Conservative           1464 2113
##   Extremely Conservative  264  459
chisq2<-chisq.test(table(gss_suicide$polviews, gss_suicide$suicide1))
chisq2
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(gss_suicide$polviews, gss_suicide$suicide1)
## X-squared = 464.36, df = 6, p-value < 2.2e-16

As shown in the chi-square output above, the p-value is a lot smaller than the significance level 0.05, and therefore we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is strong evidence suggesting that peoples views about suicide due to incurable disease and their political views are dependent.

To conclude, the research question seeks to find out if peoples attitude changed between 1977 and 2012 towards suicide with incurable disease. The analysis indeed shows that there is a significant increase in the proportion of yes responses in 2012, compared to 1977. Further more, we are 95% confident that the proportion of people who agree with suicide with incurable disease in 2012 is 13% to 21.6% higher than that in 1977.

The analysis above also shows that peoples attitude to suicide with incurable disease are related to how frequent they go to church, as well as whether they consider themselves more liberal or more conservative. However, as this is an observation study, no causal statements can be made about the relationship among these variables.

Finally, although the results can be generalized to the wider American society, we need to be aware that the collection of data does exclude certain populations, such as those who live in quarters and those who do not speak English or Spanish. For researchers who are interested in finding out the views of those particular populations, further investigation will be needed.
